<p>

At the northeastern end of the bay the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../162/368162.xml">
Department of Conservation</link> (DOC) has constructed wooden hides for the public and DOC staff to view <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../412/567412.xml">
Yellow-eyed Penguin</link>, <it>Megadyptes antipodes</it>, activity without disturbance. The beach is a popular site for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../462/910462.xml">
Hooker's Sea Lion</link>, <it>Phocarctos hookeri</it>, to bask on the sand. It is also an excellent site for washed up <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../101/13947101.xml">
Durvillea antarctica</link></it> to be found.  </p>
<p>

The bay is often thought by locals to have been named for a small biting insect known as the sandfly, but this is incorrect. It was named for the sand which, given the windy nature of this coast, flies from the tall dunes surrounding the bay. </p>
<p>

A small island which lies at the northeastern end of the bay is known as Lion Rock or Lion's Head Rock, due to its shape. A distinctive landmark, it can be clearly seen in good weather from Second Beach, close to <link>
Saint Clair</link>, 18 kilometres to the west.</p>

